60% of HCS teachers have at least a master's degree or better.<ref name=HSVCitySchools07-08AnnualReport/>

===Budgeting===
The following was the disposition of annual funding in 2007: Instructional services - 54%, Instruction support services - 15%, Operation and maintenance - 11%, capital outlay - 8%, auxiliary services - 7%, general administrative services - 3%, and debt and other expenditures - 2%.<ref name=HSVCitySchools07-08AnnualReport/>

===Higher education===
Huntsville's higher education institutions include:
* [[Alabama A&M University]]
* [[J. F. Drake State Technical College|J.F. Drake State Technical College]]
* [[Oakwood University]]
* [[University of Alabama in Huntsville]]
* [[Southeastern Institute of Technology]] (inactive)

The University of Alabama in Huntsville is the largest university serving the greater Huntsville area. The research-intensive university has more than 7,700 students. Approximately half of the university<U+2019>s graduates earn a degree in engineering or science, making the university one of the largest producers of engineers and physical scientists in Alabama. UAHuntsville has been ranked by the Carnegie Foundation as a very high research institution, placing it among the top 75 public research universities in the nation. UAHuntsville is also ranked as a Tier 1 national university by U.S. News & World Report.

Oakwood University, founded in 1896, is a [[Seventh-day Adventist Church|Seventh-day Adventist]] university with over 1,800 students and a member institution of the United Negro College Fund. It is one of the nation's leading producers of successful Black applicants to medical schools. The school was [[USCAA]] National Basketball Champions (2008) and the winner of the 19th and 20th Honda Campus All-Star Challenge National Championship Tournaments (2008 and 2009).

Various colleges and universities have satellite locations or extensions in Huntsville:
* [[Athens State University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athens.edu/ |title=Athens State University :: Building Success Stories |publisher=Athens.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Calhoun Community College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calhoun.cc.al.us/ |title=Welcome to Calhoun Community College |publisher=Calhoun.cc.al.us |date=2011-05-31 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
**[[Calhoun Community College at Cummings Research Park]]
**[[Calhoun Community College at Redstone Arsenal]]
* [[Columbia College of Missouri|Columbia College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccis.edu/nationwide/main.asp?Redstone |title=Columbia College - Redstone Arsenal: Columbia College Nationwide campuses |publisher=Ccis.edu |date=2011-10-24 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erau.edu/ |title=Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University - World's Leader in Aviation and Aerospace Education |publisher=Erau.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Faulkner University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faulkner.edu/ |title=Faulkner University - Home |publisher=Faulkner.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Florida Institute of Technology]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fit.edu/ |title=Florida Institute of Technology |publisher=Fit.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]
* Huntsville Regional Medical Campus of the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] School of Medicine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://main.uab.edu/uasom/2/show.asp?durki=3868 |title=Huntsville Campus |publisher=Main.uab.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[Virginia College]]<ref>[http://www.vc.edu/campus/huntsville-alabama-college.cfm vc.edu/huntsville]</ref>

*[[Huntsville Hospital]] and Crestwood Medical Center has an accredited school of [[radiology|radiologic technology]]<ref>[http://www.huntsvillehospital.org/services/imaging/radschool/ Huntsville Hospital School of Radiologic Technology]</ref>

==Culture==
[[File:HuntsvilleSpaceCenterRockets.jpg|frame|The U.S. Space & Rocket Center exhibits a [[Saturn I]] (left, behind trees) and a much larger (and farther back) [[Saturn V]] mock-up along with a number of other rockets illustrating the history of United States space exploration. A simulator in the foreground was built from an adapter cone from the flight model Saturn V (not pictured).]]

===Historic districts===
*[[Twickenham Historic District]] was chosen as the name of the first of three of the city's historic districts. It features homes in the Federal and Greek Revival architectural styles introduced to the city by Virginia-born [[architect]] George Steele about 1818, and contains the most dense concentration of antebellum homes in Alabama. The 1819 Weeden House Museum, home of female artist and poet Howard Weeden, is open to the public, as are several others in the district.
* [[Old Town Historic District (Huntsville, Alabama)|Old Town Historic District]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldtownhsv.org/ |title=at |publisher=Oldtownhsv.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> contains a variety of styles (Federal, Greek Revival, Queen Anne, and even California cottages), with homes dating from the late 1820s through the early 1900s.
* [[Five Points Historic District (Huntsville, Alabama)|Five Points Historic District]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fivepointshistoricdistrict.org/ |title=Five Points Historic District Association |publisher=Fivepointshistoricdistrict.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> the newest historic district, consists predominantly of bungalows built around the turn of the 20th century, by which time Huntsville was becoming a mill town.

===Museums===

* [[United States Space & Rocket Center|US Space & Rocket Center]] is home to the [[United States Space Camp|US Space Camp]] and Aviation Challenge programs as well as the only [[Saturn V]] rocket designated a [[National Historic Landmark]].
* [[Alabama Constitution Village]] features eight reconstructed Federal style buildings, with living-museums displays downtown.<ref name="earlyworks.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.earlyworks.com |title=Early Works |publisher=Early Works |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* Burritt Museum and Park, located on [[Monte Sano Mountain]], is a regional history museum featuring a 1930s mansion, nature trails, scenic overlooks and more.<ref>http://www.burrittmuseum.com</ref>
* [[Clay House Museum]]  is an antebellum home built ca. 1853 and showcases decorative styles up to 1950 and an outstanding collection of [[Noritake]] [[Porcelain]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clay-house.com/ |title=clay-house.com |publisher=clay-house.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* Early Works Museum is a child friendly interactive museum in downtown Huntsville.<ref name="earlyworks.com"/>
* Harrison Brothers Hardware Store established in 1879, is the oldest operating hardware store in Alabama. Though now owned and operated by the Historic Huntsville Foundation, it is still a working store, and part museum featuring skilled craftsmen who volunteer to run the store and answer questions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historichuntsville.org/ |title=Historic Huntsville Foundation |publisher=Historichuntsville.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harrisonbrothershardware.com |title=Historic Huntsville, Alabama |publisher=Harrison Brothers Hardware |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* The Historic [[Huntsville Depot]] completed in 1860 is the oldest surviving railroad depot in Alabama and one of the oldest surviving depots in the United States.<ref>[http://www.earlyworks.com/the-museums/train-depot]</ref>
* [[Huntsville Museum of Art]] in Big Spring International Park offers permanent displays, traveling exhibitions, and educational programs for children and adults.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvmuseum.org |title=Huntsville Museum of Art |publisher=Hsvmuseum.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* Sci-Quest is an interactive premiere hands-on museum for early childhood education, aged four through sixth grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sci-quest.org/ |title=Sci-Quest, Hands-on Science Center &#124; It's an Experiment in Fun |publisher=Sci-quest.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* [[North Alabama Railroad Museum]] is a railroad museum with over 30 pieces of rolling stock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northalabamarailroadmuseum.com |title=North Alabama Railroad Museum, Huntsville, Alabama |publisher=Northalabamarailroadmuseum.com |date=2010-11-28 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>

===Parks===
{{wide image|BigSpringPanoramic.jpg|600px|Big Spring International Park|45%|right}}

There are [[Parks and Greenways in Huntsville|57 parks within the city limits of Huntsville]].<ref>[http://www.huntsvilleal.gov/recreation/parks.php City of Huntsville - City Parks]</ref>
*[[Big Spring International Park]] is a park in downtown Huntsville centered on a natural water body (Big Spring). The park contains the Huntsville Museum of Art. Festivals are held there, such as the Panoply Arts Festival and the Big Spring Jam.  There are fish in the spring's niche.  There is a waterfall and a constantly-lit gas torch.
*[[Creekwood Park]] is a {{convert|71|acre}} park with a full-scale children's playground and dog park that connects to the [[Indian Creek Greenway]].<ref>[http://www.hsvcity.com/Web-ASP/Parks/parks.asp?pkid=19 Parks and Centers - Huntsville]</ref>
*[[Huntsville Botanical Garden]] features educational programs, woodland paths, broad grassy meadows and stunning floral collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvbg.org |title=Huntsville Botanical Garden - Home |publisher=Hsvbg.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
*[[John Hunt Park]] is the city's largest park with over {{convert|400|acres}} of open space, tennis courts, soccer fields and walking trails.<ref name=johnhuntpark>{{cite news|last=Doyle|first=Steve|title=Huntsville City Council president: improving John Hunt Park starts with removing old runway|url=http://blog.al.com/breaking/2011/04/huntsville_council_president_s.html|accessdate=10 January 2012|newspaper=The Huntsville Times|date=11 April 2011}}</ref>
*[[Land Trust of Huntsville & North Alabama]] is a member supported, non-profit organization dedicated to the conservation of the natural heritage of the area, and has preserved more than {{convert|5000|acre|km2|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of open space, wildflower areas, wetlands, working farms and scenic vistas in North Alabama, including 1,000+ acres (4.0&nbsp;km<U+00B2>) of the Monte Sano Preserve (Monte Sano Mountain), 1,000+ acres (4.0&nbsp;km<U+00B2>) of the Blevins Gap Preserve (Huntsville & Green Mountains), and {{convert|813|acre|km2|abbr=on|sigfig=3}} of the Wade Mountain Preserve.  Volunteers have created and maintain 33+ miles (53+&nbsp;km) of public trails - all of which are within the Huntsville city limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.landtrust-hsv.org |title=Land Trust North Alabama |publisher=Landtrust-hsv.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
*[[Lydia Gold Skatepark]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvcity.com/recreation/skatepark.php |title=City of Huntsville, Alabama *** Huntsville *** Alabama *** HuntsvilleAL.gov |publisher=Hsvcity.com |date=2011-04-25 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> located behind the Historic Huntsville Depot is open to the public.  In 2003, it was dedicated to the late Lydia Leigh Gold (1953<U+2013>1993), an area skateboarding activist in the 1980s and the former owner of <U+201C>Tattooed Lady Comics and Skateboards.<U+201D>  Helmets are the only pad requirement.  No bikes, scooters, or other wheeled vehicles are allowed <U+2013> only skateboards and rollerblades are permitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntsville.org/listings/index.cfm?action=display&listingID=95&hit=1 |title=Huntsville/Madison County Convention & Visitors Bureau |publisher=Huntsville.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
*[[Monte Sano State Park]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alapark.com/parks/park.cfm?parkid=6 |title=Alabama State Parks |publisher=Alapark.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> has over {{convert|2000|acre|km2|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} and features hiking and bicycling trails, rustic cabins built by the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]], campsites, full [[recreational vehicle|RV]] hook-ups, and a recently reconstructed lodge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.outdooralabama.com/photos/msphotos/ |title=Monte Sano Photos |publisher=Outdooralabama.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>

===Festivals===
*The Annual North Alabama International Festival<ref name="Annual North Alabama International Festival">{{cite web|url=http://uahlibinfo.uah.edu/php-scripts/libraryblog/index.php/2011/08/22/2nd-annual-international-festival-on-sat-oct-29/ |title=2nd Annual International Festival on Sat., Oct. 29 &#124; UAH Library Blog |publisher=Uahlibinfo.uah.edu |date=2011-08-22 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is held in October at the UAHuntsville Shelby Center for Science and Technology.  This free family event features displays from many nations, presentations, travel/historic literature, hosts in native apparel, children<U+2019>s activities, and other audio-visuals emblematic of the participating countries.  In addition, there are live performances and demos, as well as an ethnic food-tasting event and international food vendors.
*[[Big Spring Jam]] is an annual three-day music festival held on the last full weekend of September in and around Big Spring International Park in downtown Huntsville. Presented is a diversity of music including rock, country, Christian, kid-friendly, and oldies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Welch|first=Chris|title=Big Spring Jam announces headliners Saving Abel, Hinder, Old Crow Medicine Show, Earth Wind & Fire, Fuel, Manchester Orchestra|url=http://blog.al.com/entertainment-times/2011/07/huntsvilles_big_spring_jam_18.html|accessdate=September 15, 2011|newspaper=[[The Huntsville Times]]|date=July 31, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/61j4CJHXV|archivedate=September 15, 2011}}</ref>
*The [[Panoply Arts Festival]]<ref name="Panoply Arts Festival">{{cite web|url=http://www.panoply.org |title=Panoply Arts Festival |publisher=Panoply.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is an annual arts festival that began on 14 May 1982. It is presented by The Arts Council<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artshuntsville.org |title=The Arts Council |publisher=Artshuntsville.org |date=2011-05-01 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> and is held on the last full weekend of each April in Big Spring International Park and the Von Braun Center. The festival includes performance stages featuring presentations, demonstrations, performances, competitions, and workshops to promote the arts. There are children's activities, a Global Village, strolling performers, and nightly fireworks displays.  Panoply has had three record attendances in a row, averaging 100,000 for 2007, 2008, and 2009.{{Citation needed|date=December 2009}} The Southeast Tourism Society consistently ranks the festival among their "Top Twenty Events" and Governor Bob Riley has announced it as one of Alabama's top ten tourism events.<ref>{{cite web
|url         = http://www.waff.com/story/9771698/panoply-2009
|title       = Panoply 2009
|date        = 27
|month       = April
|year        = 2009
|accessdate  = October 4, 2011
}}</ref>
*[[Con<U+2020>Stellation]] is an annual general-interest science fiction convention.<ref name=scifi>{{cite web |url=http://www.con-stellation.org |title=Con*Stellation, a Science Fiction convention}}</ref> Con<U+2020>Stellation (also written as Con*Stellation) has been generally held over a Friday-Sunday weekend in October each year (as of 2012).

===Public golf courses===
* Becky Pierce Municipal Golf Course,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvcity.com/recreation/golf.php |title=Becky Pierce Municipal Golf Course |publisher=Hsvcity.com |date=2011-04-25 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> known locally as the "Muni", off Airport Road (named for the old airport, not near the current airport).
* Sunset Landing Golf Club (located next to the airport)
* Colonial Golf Course
* Fox Run Golf Course
* Redstone Arsenal Golf Course (Open to military ID holders)
* Hampton Cove<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtjgolf.com/courses/hampton_cove |title=Hampton Cove |publisher=Rtjgolf.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is one of the eleven courses making up the [[Robert Trent Jones Golf Trail]]; named after [[Hampton Cove]], it features two championship 18-hole courses and one par-three course (Huntsville, AL)
* Harvest Hills Golf Course (Harvest, AL)
* Chriswood Golf Course (Athens, AL)
* Southern Gayles (Athens, AL)
* Canebrake Club<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canebrakeclub.com |title=Canebrake Club |publisher=Canebrake Club |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> (Athens, AL)
* Richland Golf Center (Huntsville, Al)

===Private golf courses===
* Established in 1925, the historic [http://www.huntsvillecountryclub.com Huntsville Country Club] boasts a challenging 18-hole course with dining and banquet facilities located just North of downtown at 2601 Oakwood Avenue.
* The Ledges is Huntsville's newest golf community with 18 holes, dining and banquet facilities overlooking Jones Valley.
* Valley Hill Country Club features 27 holes in South Huntsville's Jones Valley.

===Libraries===
[[The Huntsville Madison County Public Library]],<ref name=hmlibrary>[http://hmcpl.org Huntsville Madison County Public Library]</ref> founded in 1818, is Alabama's oldest continually operating library system. It has 12 branches throughout the county including one [[bookmobile]]. The Main Library Archives contains a wealth of historical resources, including displays of photographic collections and artifacts, has Alabama's highest materials circulation rate, and features daily public programs. The library system provides free public access Internet computers and wireless Internet access in all facilities.

===Arts associations===
Several arts groups have passed the 50-year mark:  Huntsville Community Chorus Association; Huntsville Art League; Theatre Huntsville (through its parent company); Broadway Theatre League; Fantasy Playhouse Children<U+2019>s Theatre; Rocket City Chorus; Huntsville Symphony Orchestra; and Huntsville Photographic Society among them.{{citation needed|don't see that longevity is particularly germane to a non-history subsection. Organizations can reach "50 years" with 3 people and not actually '''do''' anything|date=November 2011}}

====The Arts Council====
Founded in October 1962 as a non-profit, [[501(c)#501(c)(3)|501(c)(3)]] organization, the Arts Council, Inc.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artshuntsville.org |title=The Arts Council, Inc. (TAC) |publisher=Artshuntsville.org |date=2011-05-01 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> (TAC) includes over 100 local arts organizations and advocates. TAC sponsors the arts through five core programs:
* Arts Education &mdash; including the <U+201C>Meet the Artist<U+201D> interactive, <U+201C>distance learning<U+201D> program at Educational Television<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etvhuntsville.com/ |title=Educational Television (ETV) |publisher=Etvhuntsville.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> and ArtVentures summer arts camp;
* Member services;
* the annual Panoply Arts Festival<ref name="Panoply Arts Festival"/>
* Concerts in the Park, a series of <U+201C>summer serenades under the stars<U+201D> held at Big Spring International Park in partnership with the City<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvcity.com/recreation/cityevnt.php |title=City of Huntsville Department of Recreation Services<U+2019> Division of Community Events |publisher=Hsvcity.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
* Community Information Services, featuring <U+201C>Boost Your Buzz,<U+201D> an annual publicity workshop.

TAC promotes the visual arts with two galleries:  art@TAC, using the walls near the company<U+2019>s Von Braun Center<ref>{{cite web|author=Shults Design http://www.shultsdesign.com |url=http://www.vonbrauncenter.com/pages/maps.html |title=Von Braun Center |publisher=Von Braun Center |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> offices and the JavaGalleria.  TAC supports The Bench Project{{clarify|need to understand it more than naming it|date=November 2011}}<ref>[http://benchproject.org/ The Bench Project]</ref> and the strategic planning effort to support Huntsville-Madison County<U+2019>s economic development goals through expanded arts and cultural opportunities known as Create Huntsville.<ref>[http://www.artshuntsville.org/our-programs/create-huntsville Create Huntsville]</ref>

===Performing arts===
{{Overly detailed|date=November 2011}}
*The Huntsville Community Chorus Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thechorus.org |title=Huntsville Community Chorus Association |publisher=Thechorus.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> (HCCA) is one of Alabama's oldest performing arts organizations, with its first performance dating to December 1946 (per its website, the Mobile Opera Guild &mdash; the state's oldest &mdash; first performed in April of that year). HCCA produces choral concerts and musical theater productions. In addition, the company features its madrigal singers; "Glitz!" (a show choir); a chamber chorale; an annual summer melodrama/fundraiser; and three children's groups: the Huntsville Community Chorus (HCC) Children's Chorale (ages 3&ndash;5); the HCC Treble Chorale (ages 6&ndash;8); and the HCC Youth Chorale (ages 9&ndash;12).
*Broadway Theatre League<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadwaytheatreleague.org |title=Broadway Theatre League |publisher=Broadway Theatre League |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> was founded in 1959. BTL presents a season of national touring Broadway productions each year, a family-fun show, and additional season specials. Shows are presented in the Von Braun Center's Mark C. Smith Concert Hall. Recent productions include ''[[Mamma Mia!]]'', ''[[A Chorus Line]]'', ''[[The Color Purple]]'', and ''An Evening with Patti LuPone and Mandy Patinkin''.
*The Flying Monkey Arts Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyingmonkeyarts.org |title=The Flying Monkey Arts Center |publisher=Flyingmonkeyarts.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is in the historic Lowe Mill under the auspices of Lowe Mill ARTS and Entertainment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lowemill.net/ |title=Lowe Mill ARTS and Entertainment |publisher=Lowemill.net |date=2011-08-19 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> and hosts events<ref>[http://www.flyingmonkeyart.org/calendar.html events]</ref> such as the traditional Cigar Box Guitar festival, the Sex Workers' Art Show, concerts, and many presentations of the Film Co-op.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcoop.org/ |title=The Film Co-op |publisher=The Film Co-op |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>
*[[Huntsville Symphony Orchestra]]<ref name=symphony>{{cite web|url=http://www.hso.org |title=Huntsville Symphony Orchestra |publisher=Hso.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is Alabama's oldest continuously operating professional symphony orchestra, featuring performances of classical, pops and family concerts, and music education programs in public schools.
*Fantasy Playhouse Children's Theatre,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letthemagicbegin.com |title=Fantasy Playhouse Children's Theatre (FP) |publisher=Letthemagicbegin.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> Huntsville's oldest children's theater, was founded in 1960. An all-volunteer organization, Fantasy Playhouse performs for the children of north Alabama on stage and off.  Fantasy Playhouse Theater Academy, the organization's dance, music, and art school, teaches children and adults each year. Fantasy Playhouse regularly produces three plays a year with an additional play, ''A Christmas Carol'', produced early each December.
*Theatre Huntsville,<ref>[http://www.theatrehsv.org Theatre Huntsville (TH)]</ref> the result of a merger between the Twickenham Repertory Company (1979<U+2013>1997) and Huntsville Little Theatre (1950<U+2013>1997), is a 501(c)(3), non-profit, all-volunteer arts organization that presents six plays each season in the Von Braun Center Playhouse. It produces the annual "Shakespeare on the Mountain" in an outdoor venue, such as Burritt on the Mountain. Presentations range from ''[[The Foreigner (play)|The Foreigner]]'' and ''[[Noises Off]]'' to the occasional musical (''[[Little Shop of Horrors (musical)|Little Shop of Horrors]]'' and ''[[Nunsense]]'').  In addition, TH presents drama-related workshops (stage management, stage makeup, etc.), as announced.
*Independent Musical Productions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imphuntsville.org |title=Independent Musical Productions (IMP) |publisher=Imphuntsville.org |date=2011-11-04 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> was founded in 1993 and presents at least one annual main production such as ''[[Ragtime]]'', ''Civil War'', ''[[1776]]'', ''Into the Woods'', ''[[RENT]]'', and ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street|Sweeney Todd]]''.  Standard and original musicals for children as well as outreach programs complete the season.
*Plays are performed at Renaissance Theatre,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renaissancetheatre.net |title=(RT) |publisher=Renaissance Theatre |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> with two stages, the MainStage (upstairs) and the Alpha Stage (downstairs), each with seating about 85. The theaters are housed in the former Commissary Building for the historic Lincoln Mill Village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collections.alabamamosaic.org/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/hmcpl1&CISOPTR=92&CISOBOX=1&REC=20 |title=Lincoln Mill Village |publisher=Collections.alabamamosaic.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renaissancetheatre.net/bio.htm |title=Renaissance Theatre Biographies |publisher=Renaissancetheatre.net |date=2006-01-11 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref>  In addition to well-known and mainstream titles, Renaissance produces original, controversial, and offbeat plays.  It was the site for the East Coast premiere of "The Maltese Falcon."
*Merrimack Hall Performing Arts Center<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merrimackhall.com |title=Merrimack Hall Performing Arts Center |publisher=Merrimackhall.com |date=2009-01-19 |accessdate=2011-11-08}}</ref> is a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization that opened in 2007, after nearly $3 million in renovations to the historic building. It was once the social center of the Merrimack Mill Village in the early 1900s. The Company Store, gymnasium, bowling alley, were all there and provided a place for socialization and recreation to all of the village's residents. Merrimack Hall now includes a 302-seat performance hall, a {{convert|3000|ft2|m2}} foot dance studio, and rehearsal and instructional spaces for musicians. Productions and performers include ''[[Menopause The Musical]]'', ''Dixie's Tupperware Party'', Billy Bob Thornton and The Boxmasters, Dionne Warwick, Lisa Loeb, Claire Lynch, and the Second City Comedy Troupe.
*[[Ars Nova School of the Arts]]<ref>[http://www.arsnovahsv.com]</ref> is a conservatory for music and performing arts.  Ars Nova  produces musical theatre, opera, and operetta for the local stage.
*The Huntsville Youth Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntsvilleyouthorchestra.org/ |title=Welcome! |publisher=Huntsvilleyouthorchestra.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> was founded by Russell Gerhart, founding conductor of the Huntsville Symphony Orchestra, in 1961. The HYO is a non-profit corporation whose purpose is to <U+201C>foster, promote, and provide the support necessary for students from North Alabama to experience musical education in an orchestral setting.<U+201D>  The organization has six ensembles: the Huntsville Youth Symphony, Sinfonia, Philharmonia, Concert Orchestra, Intermezzo Orchestra, and Novice Strings.
*Huntsville Chamber Music Guild<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntsvillechambermusicguild.uah.edu/ |title=Huntsville Chamber Music Guild |publisher=Huntsvillechambermusicguild.uah.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> was organized in 1952 to promote and present chamber music programs; the group seeks to present recitals in which artists are presented in works of the classical masters.

===Visual arts===
*The Huntsville Museum of Art<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hsvmuseum.org/ |title=Huntsville Museum of Art (HMA) |publisher=Hsvmuseum.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> opened in 1970.  It purchased the largest privately owned, permanent collection of art by American women in the U.S., featuring and [[Anna Elizabeth Klumpke]], among others.<ref>{{cite web
|url         = http://www.spacecamp.com/vacationplanner/node/53
|title       = Huntsville Museum of Art
|date        = 19
|month       = February
|year        = 2010
|work        = Attractions
|publisher   = U.S. Space & Rocket Center
|accessdate  = October 4, 2011
}}</ref>

*The Huntsville Photographic Society<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntsvillephotographicsociety.org/ |title=Huntsville Photographic Society |publisher=Huntsville Photographic Society |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> started in 1956.  A non-profit organization, the HPS is dedicated to furthering of the art and science of photography in North Alabama.

* The Huntsville Art League<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huntsvilleartleague.org/ |title=Huntsville Art League |publisher=Huntsville Art League |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> started in 1957, adopting the name <U+201C>The Huntsville Art League and Museum Association<U+201D> (HALMA).  In addition to their Visiting Artists and <U+201C>Limelight Artists<U+201D> series, which highlight both nonresident and member artists at the home office, HAL features its members<U+2019> works at galleries located in the Jane Grote Roberts Auditorium of the Huntsville-Madison County Public Library <U+2013> Main, the Heritage Club, and the halls of the Huntsville Times.

===Convention center and arena===
The [[Von Braun Center]], which originally opened in 1975 as the Von Braun Civic Center, has an arena capable of seating 10,000, a 2,000-seat concert hall, a 500-seat playhouse (~330 seats with proscenium staging), and {{convert|150000|sqft|m2|-3}} of convention space.  Both the arena and concert hall have undergone major renovations; as a result, they have been rechristened the Propst Arena and the Mark C. Smith Concert Hall, respectively.

===Other===
*The [[National Speleological Society]]<ref name=nss>{{cite web|url=http://www.caves.org/ |title=National Speleological Society (NSS) |publisher=Caves.org |date= |accessdate=2011-11-09}}</ref> is headquartered in Huntsville on Cave Street.
*The [[Von Braun Astronomical Society]]<ref name=astrosoc>[http://www.vbas.org/facilities.cfm Von Braun Astronomical Society]{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref> has two observatories and a planetarium on 10 acres (40,000&nbsp;m<U+00B2>) in Monte Sano State Park.

